amshire,England":"Flawford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Martel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Andre, Armand, Normand, Marcel, Adrien, Aime, Benoit, Laurent, Yvan, Jacques, Michel.","French and English (Guernsey): nickname for a forceful person or perhaps a metonymic occupational name for a smith, from Old French <i>martel</i> ‘hammer’ (also recorded in late Middle English), from Late Latin <i>martellus</i>. The reference may be to the <i>martel de fer</i>, the iron hammer or mace of medieval warfare, as had been the case with Charles Martel, the grandfather of Charlemagne, who gained his byname from the force with which he struck down his enemies, the Saracens, in the battle of Tours (Poitiers) in 732.","English (Guernsey): from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Martel</i>, a pet form of   Martin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Martelle","meanings":["French: from the feminine form of   Martel   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Martin","meanings":["English, Scottish, Irish, French, Walloon, Breton, Dutch, Flemish, German, Czech, Slovak, Croatian, Italian (Veneto); Spanish (<b>Martín</b>): from a personal name derived from Latin <i>Martinus</i>, itself a derivative of <i>Mars</i>, genitive <i>Martis</i>, the Roman god of fertility and war, whose name may derive ultimately from a root <i>mar</i> ‘gleam’. This was borne by a famous 4th-century Christian saint, Martin of Tours, and consequently became extremely popular throughout Europe in the Middle Ages. In North America, the surname <i>Martin</i> has absorbed cognates and derivatives from other languages, e.g. Slovak and Rusyn (from Slovakia)   Marcin  , Albanian   Martini  , Polish surnames beginning with <i>Marcin-</i>, and Slovenian patronymics like <b>Martinčič</b> (see   Martincic  ). <i>Martin</i> is the most frequent surname in France and one of the most frequent surnames in Wallonia.","English: variant of   Marton  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mártain</b>, ‘descendant of Martin’ (compare 1 above). Otherwise, a shortened form of   Gilmartin   or   McMartin  ; sometimes also spelled <i>Martyn</i>."]},{"name":"Martell","meanings":["French: rare southern variant of   Martel   (compare 2 below) and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this.","Catalan: nickname for a forceful person or perhaps a metonymic occupational name for a smith, from <i>martell</i> ‘hammer’ (from Late Latin <i>martellus</i>; see also   Martel   1).","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Martel  ."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":54,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":63,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":98,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Adam Martel was born in Flawford, Nottinghamshire, England as the son of Geoffrey Martel. He had at least 1 son. He died before 1281, in Flawford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"–bef 1281":"–enne 1281","1215–1284":"1215–1284","–1281":"–1281","1276–1345":"1276–1345","–1280":"–1280","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1345":"1345","bef 1280":"enne 1280","bef 1281":"enne 1281","1276":"1276","1284":"1284","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","Flawford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Flawford, Nottinghamshire, England","Flawford,Nottinghamshire,England":"Flawford, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"–bef 1281":"–ennen vuotta 1281","1215–1284":"1215–1284","–1281":"–1281","1276–1345":"1276–1345","–1280":"–1280","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1345":"1345","bef 1280":"ennen vuotta 1280","bef 1281":"ennen vuotta 1281","1276":"1276","1284":"1284","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","Flawford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Flawford, Nottinghamshire, England","Flawford,Nottinghamshire,England":"Flawford, Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"–bef 1281":"–avant 1281","1215–1284":"1215–1284","–1281":"–1281","1276–1345":"1276–1345","–1280":"–1280","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1345":"1345","bef 1280":"avant 1280","bef 1281":"avant 1281","1276":"1276","1284":"1284","1281":"1281","1280":"1280","Flawford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Flawford, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","Flawford,Nottinghamshire,England":"Flawford, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Adam Martel est né à Flawford, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, fils de Geoffrey Martel. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé avant 1281, à Flawford, Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"–bef 1281":"–vor 1281","1215–1284":"1215–1284","–1281":"–1281","1276–1345":"1276–1345","–1280":"–1280","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1345":"1345